<section id="the-alzheimers-signal" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Alzheimer's Signal</h2>
  <p>Back to the brain. The Dominy et al. (2019) finding deserves precise treatment, because it is both the most dramatic data point in this literature and the most preliminary. What the study showed: <em>P. gingivalis</em> infection in mice produced Alzheimer's-like pathology, including amyloid-beta production. In human brain tissue from deceased Alzheimer's patients, gingipains — the toxic proteases produced by <em>P. gingivalis</em> — were detected in 96% of samples and correlated with tau and ubiquitin pathology. The researchers also identified <em>P. gingivalis</em> in the cerebrospinal fluid of living Alzheimer's patients.</p>
  <p>This is not proof that <em>P. gingivalis</em> causes Alzheimer's disease. It is proof that a periodontal pathogen can reach the brain, and that its presence correlates with disease markers. Those are different claims, and conflating them is how this story gets oversold and then dismissed.</p>
  <p>The plausible route: oral bacteria and their metabolites cross the blood-brain barrier via several proposed mechanisms — direct bacteremia reaching cerebral vasculature, LPS-driven neuroinflammation, and bacterial amyloids that may seed or accelerate amyloid-beta aggregation. A 2020 review in <em>Journal of Alzheimer's Disease</em> (Ilievski et al.) demonstrated that repeated intranasal inoculation of <em>P. gingivalis</em> in mice produced brain colonization and increased amyloid-beta production. Independent replication of the human brain tissue findings has been reported by researchers at the University of Auckland and elsewhere.</p>
  <p>What remains genuinely unknown: whether treating periodontal disease in midlife reduces Alzheimer's risk. The longitudinal data is suggestive — a 2020 cohort study in <em>Journal of the American Geriatrics Society</em> (Kaye et al., n=262, 20-year follow-up) found that tooth loss, a proxy for severe periodontal disease, was associated with accelerated cognitive decline — but cohort data cannot rule out shared risk factors. A pharmaceutical company, Cortexyme, developed a gingipain inhibitor (COR388) that entered Phase 2/3 trials for Alzheimer's. The trial results were mixed, which is either evidence against the causal hypothesis or evidence that intervening at the symptomatic stage of Alzheimer's is too late. Probably some of both.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"<em>P. gingivalis</em> gingipains were detected in 96% of Alzheimer's brain tissue samples — and correlated with tau pathology. This is not proof of causation. It is proof that a mouth bacterium can reach the brain."</p></aside>

<section id="rheumatoid-arthritis-the-molecular-mimicry-angle" class="reveal">
  <h2>Rheumatoid Arthritis: The Molecular Mimicry Angle</h2>
  <p>The oral-rheumatoid arthritis connection is mechanistically distinct from the cardiovascular and neurological pathways, and arguably more elegant. <em>P. gingivalis</em> is the only known bacterium that expresses its own peptidylarginine deiminase (PPAD) enzyme — an enzyme that citrullinates proteins by converting arginine residues to citrulline. Anti-citrullinated protein antibodies (ACPAs) are the defining autoimmune marker of rheumatoid arthritis, present in roughly 70% of RA patients and often detectable years before clinical disease onset.</p>
  <p>The hypothesis: <em>P. gingivalis</em>-driven citrullination of host proteins in the gingival tissue generates neoantigens that trigger ACPA production, which then cross-reacts with citrullinated proteins in synovial joints. This is molecular mimicry with a named organism and a named enzyme. A 2016 study in <em>Science Translational Medicine</em> (Konig et al.) demonstrated that ACPA-positive RA patients showed elevated immune responses to <em>P. gingivalis</em>-citrullinated antigens compared to ACPA-negative patients and healthy controls.</p>
  <p>The 2026 PMC synthesis confirmed that periodontal disease prevalence is significantly elevated in RA patients compared to controls across multiple systematic reviews, with the association persisting after adjustment for smoking — itself a shared risk factor for both conditions. <em>P. gingivalis</em> has been detected in synovial fluid and synovial tissue of RA patients in independent studies from Japan, Sweden, and the United States.</p>
  <p>Again, the intervention data is imperfect. Periodontal treatment in RA patients has shown modest reductions in disease activity scores (DAS28) in small RCTs, but the effect sizes are inconsistent and the trials underpowered. The mechanistic case is stronger than the intervention case. That gap is frustrating, but it is the honest state of the evidence.</p>
</section>

<section id="why-the-gut-got-the-spotlight" class="reveal">
  <h2>Why the Gut Got the Spotlight</h2>
  <p>The gut microbiome story broke into mainstream consciousness around 2012, propelled by a handful of high-profile <em>Nature</em> and <em>Science</em> papers, the Human Microbiome Project's first major publications, and a media ecosystem hungry for a unified theory of chronic disease. The narrative was irresistible: a hidden organ, containing more cells than the human body itself, governing everything from mood to immunity to metabolic health. The gut got Rob Knight, it got the TED talks, it got the $4 billion research funding wave.</p>
  <p>The oral microbiome got dentistry. And dentistry, in the academic and cultural hierarchy of medicine, has always been the poor relation — literally separated from medical schools, excluded from most national health insurance systems, and treated as a cosmetic specialty with occasional clinical relevance. The silo is not accidental. It is structural, historical, and self-reinforcing.</p>
  <p>The result is a literature that is 30-plus systematic reviews deep, with identified organisms, identified mechanisms, and population-level effect sizes that would generate front-page coverage if they were attached to a gut bacterium — sitting largely unread outside specialist periodontology journals. A 2022 analysis in <em>BMC Oral Health</em> noted that despite the volume of oral-systemic research, integration of periodontal assessment into primary care and cardiology guidelines remains inconsistent across most Western healthcare systems.</p>
  <p>The research funding asymmetry is real. NIH funding for gut microbiome research has consistently dwarfed oral microbiome funding over the past decade, despite the oral microbiome's comparably complex ecology and arguably more direct systemic access routes. This is not a conspiracy. It is how scientific attention works: momentum begets funding begets momentum, and the oral microbiome never got the initial momentum.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The oral microbiome got dentistry. And dentistry, in the academic hierarchy of medicine, has always been the poor relation — literally separated from medical schools, excluded from most national health insurance systems."</p></aside>

<section id="what-the-evidence-cannot-yet-say" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Evidence Cannot Yet Say</h2>
  <p>Intellectual honesty requires a full accounting of the limitations, because the story is strong enough to survive them and weak enough to be destroyed by overstating them.</p>
  <p>Reverse causation is a genuine problem. Systemic disease — diabetes, cardiovascular disease, immunosuppression — alters the oral microbiome. Patients with chronic illness may have worse oral hygiene due to medication side effects, reduced mobility, or economic precarity. Disentangling cause from consequence in cross-sectional and even prospective cohort data is genuinely difficult, and most of the 30-plus systematic reviews acknowledge this explicitly.</p>
  <p>Confounding by socioeconomic status is pervasive. Periodontal disease, smoking, poor diet, physical inactivity, and limited healthcare access cluster together in low-income populations. Adjusting for these variables statistically is not the same as eliminating their influence, and residual confounding is a legitimate concern in virtually every study in this literature.</p>
  <p>The intervention trials have not delivered. If periodontal disease causes cardiovascular events, treating periodontal disease should reduce cardiovascular events. The PERIODONT and INVEST trials showed reductions in inflammatory biomarkers but not in hard clinical endpoints. This is a serious evidentiary gap. It does not disprove the association, but it prevents the field from claiming a causal chain with confidence.</p>
  <p>And the oral microbiome contains 700-plus species. Attributing systemic effects to specific organisms — even well-studied ones like <em>P. gingivalis</em> — requires isolating their contribution from a complex, interacting ecosystem. The keystone pathogen model, in which <em>P. gingivalis</em> destabilizes the entire oral community at low abundance, is compelling but still debated in the periodontology literature (Hajishengallis et al., <em>Nature Reviews Microbiology</em>, 2012).</p>
  <p>None of this makes the oral-systemic axis a fringe hypothesis. It makes it a maturing field with real mechanistic evidence, real epidemiological signal, and real methodological challenges that have not yet been fully resolved. That is a description of most important science.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-equity-dimension" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Equity Dimension</h2>
  <p>Dental care is among the most socioeconomically stratified forms of healthcare in the developed world. In the United States, Medicaid covers dental care for children but adult dental benefits are optional for states, and most states provide only emergency coverage. Medicare, the federal insurance program for Americans over 65 — precisely the population at highest risk for cardiovascular disease and Alzheimer's — did not include comprehensive dental benefits until very recently, and coverage remains limited and inconsistently implemented.</p>
  <p>The result: approximately 74 million Americans lack dental insurance, according to KFF (Kaiser Family Foundation) estimates. Dental visits are strongly correlated with income — adults in the lowest income quartile are roughly half as likely to have seen a dentist in the past year as adults in the highest income quartile, per CDC National Health Interview Survey data. Severe periodontitis, the phenotype most consistently associated with systemic disease risk in the literature, is two to three times more prevalent in low-income populations.</p>
  <p>If the oral microbiome is a mechanistically plausible driver of cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, and neurodegeneration — and 30-plus systematic reviews suggest it is — then the century-old administrative silo separating dentistry from medicine is not just an academic inconvenience. It is a structural determinant of health that compounds existing inequities. The people least likely to access dental care are the same people most likely to carry the systemic disease burden that the oral-systemic literature links to periodontal pathology.</p>
  <p>That is not a coincidence. It is a policy failure dressed up as a specialty boundary.</p>
  <p>The 74 million Americans without dental insurance are not making a lifestyle choice. They are running an experiment in oral-systemic disease that nobody designed, nobody consented to, and nobody is measuring with the rigor the question deserves.</p>
</section>

